Overview

This report visualizes the most common words used by two senior UN officials at the press conference for the release of the most recent International Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) report: UN Secretary General Antonio Guterres and United Nations Environment Programme director Inger Andersen. Sentiment analysis of the speeches is also presented. The speeches were recorded live on YouTube, and the speech text was obtained from YouTubeâ€™s transcription feature.

Data Citation: IPCC Press Conference - Climate Change 2022: Impacts, Adaptation, and Vulnerability. Recorded 2022-02-28. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JpK7eeYRhjQ

Citation for NRC lexicon: Crowdsourcing a Word-Emotion Association Lexicon, Saif Mohammad and Peter Turney, Computational Intelligence, 29 (3), 436-465, 2013.

Setup

Read in data

andersen_text <- pdf_text(here('data', 'ipcc_anderson.pdf'))
guterres_text <- pdf_text(here('data', 'ipcc_guterres.pdf'))

Initial wrangling

andersen_words <- data.frame(andersen_text) %>% 
  mutate(page = 1:n()) %>%
  mutate(text_full = str_split(andersen_text, pattern = '\\n')) %>% 
  unnest(text_full) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_trim(text_full)) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text_full) %>% 
  select(-andersen_text)

guterres_words <- data.frame(guterres_text) %>% 
  mutate(page = 1:n()) %>%
  mutate(text_full = str_split(guterres_text, pattern = '\\n')) %>% 
  unnest(text_full) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_trim(text_full)) %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text_full) %>% 
  select(-guterres_text)

Remove stop words and numbers

andersen_words_clean <- andersen_words %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words, by = 'word') %>% 
  filter(word != 'uh', word != 'dr', word != 'g') # removing common words and typos that don't have significant meaning in this context

andersen_words_clean$word <- gsub('[0-9.]', '', andersen_words_clean$word) # remove numeric symbols

guterres_words_clean <- guterres_words %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words, by = 'word') %>% 
  filter(word != 'uh', word != 'dr', word != 'g')

guterres_words_clean$word <- gsub('[0-9.]', '', guterres_words_clean$word)

Count word occurrence

andersen_clean_count <- andersen_words_clean %>% 
  count(word)

guterres_clean_count <- guterres_words_clean %>% 
  count(word)

Create word clouds

andersen_top50 <- andersen_clean_count %>% 
  arrange(-n) %>% 
  slice(1:50)

guterres_top50 <- guterres_clean_count %>% 
  arrange(-n) %>% 
  slice(1:50)
andersen_cloud <- 
  ggplot(data = andersen_top50, aes(label = word)) +
  geom_text_wordcloud(aes(color = n, size = n), shape = "diamond") +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 30) +
  scale_color_gradientn(colors = c("lightskyblue3","royalblue1","royalblue4")) +
  theme_minimal()

guterres_cloud <- 
  ggplot(data = guterres_top50, aes(label = word)) +
  geom_text_wordcloud(aes(color = n, size = n), shape = "diamond") +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 30) +
  scale_color_gradientn(colors = c("lightskyblue3","royalblue1","royalblue4")) +
  theme_minimal()

Takeaways from comparing most frequently used words

  • Guterresâ€™s speech seems to be more focused on energy; some of the most frequently used words are â€œenergyâ€, â€œcoalâ€, â€œfuelâ€, and â€œemissions.â€
  • By contrast, Andersenâ€™s speech is more focused on nature, using words like â€œnatureâ€, â€œenvironmentâ€, â€œbiodiversityâ€, and â€œconserve.â€
  • Guterresâ€™s speech also emphasizes large sociopolitical systems, while Andersenâ€™s speech focuses on personal, firsthand language. We see this through Guterresâ€™s discussion of â€œbanksâ€, â€œeconomyâ€, â€œsecurityâ€, â€œfinanceâ€, and â€œmultilateralâ€.
  • Andersen, on the other hand, uses an extended metaphor of global warming as an assailant on humanityâ€™s unified body through words like â€œblowsâ€ and â€œwoundsâ€, and includes more human-scale, evocative, and softer language such as â€œcommunitiesâ€, â€œagreeingâ€, â€œchannelingâ€, â€œboosting,â€ and â€œabsorbingâ€.

Sentiment analysis

andersen_nrc <- andersen_words_clean %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc"))
guterres_nrc <- guterres_words_clean %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc"))
andersen_nrc_counts <- andersen_nrc %>% 
  count(sentiment) %>% 
  mutate(speaker = 'Andersen')

guterres_nrc_counts <- guterres_nrc %>% 
  count(sentiment) %>% 
  mutate(speaker = 'Guterres')

combined_nrc_counts <- bind_rows(andersen_nrc_counts, guterres_nrc_counts)
ggplot(data = combined_nrc_counts, aes(x = sentiment, y = n)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightslategray","lightgoldenrod3")) +
  geom_col(aes(fill = speaker), position = 'dodge', width = 0.7) +
  labs(x = "Sentiment", y = "Count", fill = "Speaker") + 
  theme_minimal()

Figure 3. Sentiment analysis of Andersenâ€™s and Guterresâ€™s speeches using NRC sentiment lexicon.

Takeaways from NRC sentiment analysis

  • Guterresâ€™s speech scored higher on all measurements except positivity â€” both speeches were equally positive.
  • Andersenâ€™s speech had a higher ratio of positive language to negative language
  • Andersenâ€™s speech used more neutral language as measured by the NRC sentiment lexicon: Guterresâ€™s speech had more instances of language in almost every category, including positive sentiments such as joy and negative sentiments such as fear.

Setup for AFINN sentiment comparison

andersen_afinn <- andersen_words_clean %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn"), by = 'word')

guterres_afinn <- guterres_words_clean %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn"), by = 'word')

andersen_afinn_counts <- andersen_afinn %>% 
  count(value) %>% 
  mutate(speaker = 'Andersen')

guterres_afinn_counts <- guterres_afinn %>% 
  count(value) %>% 
  mutate(speaker = 'Guterres')

combined_afinn_counts <- bind_rows(andersen_afinn_counts, guterres_afinn_counts)
ggplot(data = combined_afinn_counts, aes(x = value, y = n)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("lightslategray","lightgoldenrod3")) +
  geom_col(aes(fill = speaker), position = 'dodge', width = 0.7) +
  labs(x = "Sentiment", y = "Count", fill = "Speaker") + 
  theme_minimal()

Figure 4. Sentiment analysis of Andersenâ€™s and Guterresâ€™s speeches using AFINN sentiment lexicon.

Takeaways from AFINN sentiment analysis

  • Using AFINN lexicon sentiment analysis, we more clearly see the trend that Andersenâ€™s speech is more positive than Guterresâ€™s speech
  • We see that Guterresâ€™s speech is significantly more negative than positive in language used. Andersenâ€™s speech appears slightly more positive than negative.
